        "rule": "Q1=b. Not meeting FoI4. At least one correct selection in Q2 from {1,5} (option 2 may or may not be selected), AND at least one correct selection in Q3 from {2,3,7}. Total correct selections across Q2+Q3 > total incorrect selections."
      },
      {
        "id": "FoI2P",
        "credit": 1,
        "rule": "Q1=b. At least one correct selection in Q2 or Q3, but either (a) all correct selections are confined to a single item (Q2-only or Q3-only), OR (b) one or more critical misconceptions are selected in Q2 {3,4,6} or Q3 {4,5,6}, OR (c) total incorrect selections ≥ total correct selections."
      },
      {
        "id": "FoI1",
        "credit": 0,
        "rule": "Q1=b. No correct selections in Q2 and Q3, or only subjective/irrelevant/don’t-know style selections (i.e., only options from Q2 {3,4,6} and Q3 {4,5,6})."
      },
      {
        "id": "FoI0",
        "credit": 0,
        "rule": "Missing or non-responsive (no selections on both Q2 and Q3)."
      }
    ],
    "notes": "Formal keying supports PCM/PC by awarding higher credit for explicit coordination of statistical and practical significance (FoI4), mid credit for sound practical reasoning without full integration (FoI3P), and low credit for partial or procedurally flawed reasoning (FoI2P). Selecting critical misconceptions suppresses credit."
  },
  "note": "Difficulty is targeted near the CR version by requiring coordination of practical magnitude with statistical evidence for top credit. Distractors encode common misconceptions: conflating p-values with importance, overgeneralizing representativeness, confusing sample size with importance, and demanding irrelevant details. Correct options are homogeneous and focus on magnitude, thresholds, CI/effect sizes, and design constraints."
}

